From: Trung Le <trung.le@ruby-journal.com>
Subject: cleanup: replace hardcoded paths in .src files with CDE_*_TOP
 placeholders (Phase 3)

This is Phase 3 of the FHS-compliance refactor. Phase 1 made the four
installation roots packager-overridable; Phase 2 converted ~78 raw
"/usr/dt/...", "/etc/dt/...", "/var/dt/..." string literals in C/C++
sources to use the CDE_*_TOP macros. This phase does the equivalent
cleanup for the build-time-preprocessed .src files.

Each .src file under programs/types/, programs/dtlogin/config/,
programs/dtsession/, programs/dt{file,imsstart,printegrate,searchpath,
config/sun}/, and programs/dtksh/examples/ goes through tradcpp at
build time with -DCDE_INSTALLATION_TOP=$(CDE_INSTALLATION_TOP) etc.
Many .src files already used the CDE_INSTALLATION_TOP token correctly;
others contained literal "/usr/dt/..." text that was therefore baked
into the installed file regardless of what the packager configured.

This patch replaces those literals with the matching tradcpp tokens:

    /usr/dt   ->  CDE_INSTALLATION_TOP
    /etc/dt   ->  CDE_CONFIGURATION_TOP
    /var/dt   ->  CDE_LOGFILES_TOP

programs/types/Makefile.am gains -DCDE_LOGFILES_TOP= so that the two
.src files in that directory referencing /var/dt (dtappman.dt.src,
dtfile.dt.src) get correctly substituted.

Files left intentionally untouched:
  * programs/types/actions.fs - dead code (not in BUILT_SOURCES,
    not installed by any Makefile, untouched since the 1996 import).
  * programs/types/dtmail.dt and dtcm.dt - shipped as-is, not
    preprocessed; would need to be renamed to .dt.src and added
    to BUILT_SOURCES. Future cleanup.
  * programs/dtprintinfo/dtprintinfo.msg.src and
    programs/dtsession/dtsession.msg.src - the literal "/usr/dt"
    references in these .msg.src files appear in user-facing UI
    strings or translator notes, not in code paths.

After this phase, building with --with-cde-config-dir=/etc/cde
produces an install tree where /usr/dt/config/Xsession.d/0010.dtpaths
contains "/etc/cde/config/Xsession.d", not "/etc/dt/config/Xsession.d".
